      "q2": {
        "id": "p_2025_q2",
        "question": "Explain why the Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955\u201356) was successful. (12 marks)",
        "stimulus": [
          "Montgomery Improvement Association (MIA)",
          "US Supreme Court"
        ],
        "clue": "Explain the excellent organization and carpools by the MIA, the ultimate legal victory in the Supreme Court (Browder v Gayle), and a third factor like the unity of the Black community around Rosa Parks or the leadership of Martin Luther King.",
        "model": "\u201COne reason why the Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955\u201356) was successful was the outstanding local organisation by the Montgomery Improvement Association (MIA).\u201D Instead of using buses, the MIA organised a complex and highly effective [[carpool system]] involving over 300 vehicles, alongside reduced-fare taxi rides from Black drivers, to ensure that Black workers could still travel to their jobs. This was kickstarted by [[Jo Ann Robinson]] distributing 35,000 leaflets. {{Therefore, the boycott was successful because this logistical network allowed the Black community to sustain the boycott for [[381 days]] without being starved into submission by the city's authorities.}}\n\n\u201CAnother reason why it was successful was the severe economic pressure the boycott placed on local authorities and businesses.\u201D Because Black Americans made up roughly [[70%]] of bus riders in Montgomery, their year-long refusal to pay fares threatened the local bus company with bankruptcy and damaged downtown merchants. This solidarity was solidified by the respect for [[Rosa Parks]], whose arrest united the community. {{Therefore, this led to success because the city authorities simply could not afford to maintain segregation if it meant the total financial ruin of their transport system.}}\n\n\u201CA final reason for its success was the parallel legal strategy that reached the highest courts.\u201D While the boycott applied economic pressure on the streets, the [[NAACP]] successfully took the case to the federal courts. In 1956, the US Supreme Court upheld the ruling in [[Browder v. Gayle]], definitively declaring that segregation on Montgomery buses was unconstitutional based on the precedent set by the [[Brown v. Topeka]] case. {{Therefore, the boycott ultimately succeeded because the Supreme Court forced the state of Alabama to legally change its discriminatory laws, overriding local resistance.}}\n\nIn conclusion, the boycott was successful because the sheer economic endurance and organisation of the grassroots movement gave civil rights lawyers the time and leverage needed to win the ultimate legal victory in the Supreme Court."
      },
